1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 1st Session of the 60th Legislature (2025)
4
5
6 AS INTRODUCED
7 An Act relating to crimes and punishments; defining
terms; making certain acts unlawful; providing
8 penalties; providing for codification; and providing
an effective date.
9
10
11 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
12 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
13 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 540D of Title 21, unless there
14 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
15 A. As used in this section:
16 1. "First responder" shall include a peace officer as defined
17 in Section 99 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes, a correctional
18 or probation and parole officer, and an emergency medical technician
19 or emergency medical care provider; and
20 2. "Harass" means to willfully engage in a course of conduct
21 directed at a first responder which intentionally causes substantial
22 emotional distress in that first responder and serves no legitimate
23 purpose.
24
Req. No. 10034 Page 1
1 B. It shall be unlawful for a person, after receiving a verbal
2 warning not to approach from a person he or she knows or reasonably
3 should know is a first responder, who is engaged in the lawful
4 performance of a legal duty, to knowingly and willfully violate such
5 warning and approach or remain within twenty-five (25) feet of the
6 first responder with the intent to:
7 1. Impede or interfere with the ability of the first responder
8 to perform such duty;
9 2. Threaten the first responder with physical harm; or
10 3. Harass the first responder.
11 C. Any person who violates the provisions of this section
12 shall, upon conviction, be guilty of a misdemeanor punishable by
13 imprisonment in the county jail for a term not to exceed one (1)
14 year, or by a fine not to exceed One Thousand Dollars ($1,000.00),
15 or by both such fine and imprisonment.
16 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
